etymologies: early 16th century; earliest use found in Statutes Prohemium Iohannis Rastell. From alnage + -er

definitions: An officer appointed to examine woollen cloth and certify its quality.

notes.text: The position of alnager was formally abolished under English law in 1699. The title of "Great Alnager of Ireland" continued in use as a courtesy title of the Baron de Blaquiere until the death of the 6th Baron in 1920.
